TICK-BORNE ENCEPHALITIS - RUSSIA (ARKHANGELSK, NOVOSIBIRSK)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] Arkhangelsk Oblast
[2] Novosibirsk Oblast
******
[1] Arkhangelsk Oblast
Date: Fri 13 Jul 2007
Source: Regnum News Agency [in Russian, trans. Mod.NP, edited]
<http://www.regnum.ru/news/856347.html>

As of 12 Jul 2007, 5346 persons, including 1501 children, have
experienced tick-bites in the Arkhangelsk Oblast. These data have
been provided by the Epidemiology Department of the Rospotrebnadzor
[Federal Service for Monitoring Consumer Rights Protection and Human
Welfare] office in the Arkhangelsk Oblast. The number of tick-bites
has increased by 28 percent in comparison with the same period last
year [2006].
The greatest numbers of tick-bites have been recorded in the Velsky
region (713), followed by the towns of Kotlas (516) & Koryazhma (425),
and the regions of Kotlas (392), Krasnoborsky (351), Konoshsky (356),
Ustyansky (350), Verkhnetoyemsky (350), Shenkursky (291), Hyandomsky
(270), Vinogradovsky (233), Plesetsk (205), Onega (208), and
Kargopolsky (185).
A total of 2841 persons have received immune preventive treatment
against TBE [Tick-borne encephalitis], representing 53 per cent of
those with tick-bites who have sought treatment. Among the adult
population, 1513 people have received immune preventive treatment
(39.3 percent of [those] who sought medical treatment). Of the
children who received medical aid, 1328 (88.5 per cent) were given
immunoglobulin.
As of 12 Jul [2007], tick control measures have been undertaken in an
area of 231.39 hectares [about 572 acres]. A total of 97 persons have
been admitted to hospital on suspicion of TBE, and the diagnosis has
been confirmed in 40 patients.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed-rus@promedmail.org>
******
[2] Novosibirsk Oblast
Date: Fri 13 Jul 2007
Source: NGS.Novosti News Agency [in Russian, trans. Mod.NP, edited]
<http://news.ngs.ru/more/29491.php>

Tamara Jufimtseva, deputy head of the epidemiology department of the
local office of Rospotrebnadzor, has stated that 2 elderly men have
died from tick-borne encephalitis (TBE) in the Novosibirsk Oblast.
She added, "One of the deceased, a 74-year-old pensioner, had sought
treatment only after 3 weeks of illness, and the other was an
unvaccinated 60-year-old man.
According to the medical authorities in the Oblast the number of
people who have died as a result of contracting TBE during the
current epidemic season has increased to 6, one of whom was a child.
Last year [2006], 4 persons died in the Novosibirsk Oblast.
At the present time, there are 446 persons in hospital with a
tentative diagnosis of TBE in the Novosibirsk Oblast, including 42
children under 14 years of age and 53 teenagers under 18 years.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed-rus@promedmail.org>
[A map of the administrative regions of Russia showing the location
of Archangelsk Oblast in the north and Novosibirsk Oblast in the
south can be accessed at
<http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/37/Russian-regions.png>.
The risk of TBE infection extends across the whole of Russia and is
increasing. - Mod.CP]
